    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct V&V 40 factor addresses iterative solution convergence tolerances and round-off accumulation in the linear algebra kernel. For this implicit static analysis using Ansys Mechanical's sparse direct solver (SPARSE), no iterative convergence criterion is applied — the direct solver produces a machine-precision factorization at each load step. Residual force convergence is monitored via Newton-Raphson equilibrium checks (tolerance 0.1% of reference force norm), and all load steps converged without bisection. Because the direct solver eliminates the iterative-convergence failure mode that this factor is designed to detect, and because the Newton-Raphson residual histories are archived as supplementary evidence, this factor is scoped out of the formal credibility scoring. The scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team lead."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses the risk that analyst input errors (incorrect boundary conditions, unit mismatches, misapplied material assignments) corrupt the simulation result. For this study, the FEA models were independently constructed by three separate analyst teams (FDA/CDRH, Ansys ACS, DePuy Synthes) following a common modeling protocol document, and all three ensemble members produced QoI predictions within 3.2% of each other. This multi-analyst, multi-tool ensemble approach provides a structural check against systematic use error that exceeds what a single-model use-error review would provide. Additionally, all boundary condition definitions and material card assignments were peer-reviewed against the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry drawings. Given the ensemble redundancy and documented peer review, the marginal credibility contribution of a separate use-error scoring exercise is negligible, and the factor is scoped out to avoid double-counting evidence already captured under model form and software quality assurance."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
